textDisplay: +Rassa h *'I'm not the one saying the cities in China are not valuable'*  You said the money was burned, so yes, you are.   *'The market is, by having them be currently unoccupied.'*  No, what the market says is that there is a mismatch in terms of standards.  The apartments built are luxury condos and what people need is affordable  housing.  But really, it's not an affair of markets. China wants 6%-7% growth and  will build just about anything to meet that self imposed target. Building  empty cities may be a spectacular but it way well be the safest way of  achieving that. I can think of a million ways the Chinese government could  screw up with that money. Given the fact that the majority of Chinese  citizens live in substandard housing, this appears less risky than what Mao  did during the Great Leap forward.   *'I'm saying the trend was obviously not there, was miscalculated'*  I don't think you understand. China is not really a market economy. It's a  planned economy, at least at the government level. So the government  mandates that cities be built here and there and they are then bringing in  people and jobs into those cities. Obviously this kind of stuff would never  fly over here, the government can't go into the countryside and says: Oi!  You! You go there and be quiet!', it's just not how things work in Europe  or in the US. But really what I'm getting at is that, you don't need to have demand to  build things because you can create the demand later. Private businesses in  market economies don't do that on a massive scale because they can never  justify the risks. But they do it on a smaller scale and try to reassure  their investors with carefully crafted business plans and promises of high  returns.  The exception is when they have deep pockets and plan on losing money for a  some time while they are creating the demand. That's the whole idea behind  marketing, it's creating a demand that isn't there or changing one need  into another need.  When Apple launched the iPod, there weren't millions of people crying out  for that product, the demand did not exist. More specifically, it was not  formulated and Apple did that. Elements of that demand existed (the fact  that people had to carry their CDs and mini discs around) but what Apple  did is create a product and only then got people hooked on it using clever  marketing.  And by the way, have you ever heard of failed products and ventures? Every  company's got them. Well yeah, those are instances where they fail to  create the demand.  Command and control governments like China essentially act as giant  corporations with deep pockets and a monopoly. Their development is  reminiscent of the strategy that was employed in my country, France, during  the post war decades. The style of economic management was called  'dirigisme'. It produced some of the best infrastructure in the world,  nuclear weapons, the most advanced civilian nuclear industry, Concorde the  supersonic plane, the fastest train in the world, an ancestor to the  internet, Ariane rockets into space etc etc...  The Chinese government is essentially doing the same thing, trying to  design the economy rather than letting it grow organically.
